ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Also see: <http://bdnews24.com/details.php?id=171819&cid=13>
At some point it would be of interest to have an estimate of the
numbers of infected cattle that were slaughtered and butchered.

Analysing human samples in a veterinary diagnostic laboratory is not
unknown and for a disease more frequently seen in livestock than
humans, it may have a positive purpose. At one time I had to
investigate the PH (public health) and veterinary services in the
Caribbean vis-a-vis zoonotic diseases. On one island the 2 services
essentially shared the same facility but with necropsies and
autopsies done in different wings. It made economic sense. The
problems come when animal samples go to a public health laboratory as
the pathogens can differ as to major species and growth characteristics.

For example a PH laboratory comfortable with culturing _M.
tuberculosis_ will traditionally always come up negative with _M.
bovis_ as the latter will not grow on the _M.tb_ media. This is
patently a learning experience for the Bangladesh health services. - Mod.MHJ]
